Introduction

This document seeks to answer the prediction question:

How well can you predict letting rates on AirBNB?

The goal of this investigation therefore is to construct a robust predictive model with minimal error and maximal predictive accuracy.

This is done by:

  • Firstly, cleaning the data and one-hot encoding some categorical variables so they may be used in a numerical model. This was a critical stage in answering this question. By avoiding removing too many columns and rows there are more data points for the model to use.
  • Secondly, investigating variable importances and iterating model specifications to optimise a random forest model. Intially a model is trained with the Air_BnB data alone and then it is uspplemented with POI data. This gives an approximation of how central the Air_BnB is to towns and therefore introduces a spatial component to the analysis greater than just longitude and latitude. A random forest model was selected to answer this question because they are able to deal with high dimensional, non-linear data, like the data we have here.
  • Thirdly, to verify and contextualise the success of the model, an XGBoost model is fitted using the same variables.

Preprocessing

Here, only the relevant columns were read into the R environment to save computation. The dropped columns were fro a variety of reasons: they were either irrelevant to the question, contained repeated or very similar information as other variables, or the columns were mostly (or entirely) empty.

the dropped columns were: - url (irrelevant) - scrape_id (irrelevant) - last_scraped (irrelevant) - source (irrelevant) - picture_url (irrelevant) - host_url (irrelevant) - host_thumbnail_url (irrelevant) - host_picture_url (irrelevant) - neighbourhood_group_cleansed (empty) - bathrooms (empty) - bedrooms (empty) - amenities (empty) - minimum_nights (repeated information) - maximum_nights (repeated information) - minimum_minimum_nights (repeated information) - maximum_minimum_nights (repeated information) - minimum_maximum_nights (repeated information) - maximum_maximum_nights(repeated information) - calendar_updated (empty) - calendar_last_scraped (irrelevant) - license (irrelevant)

# one-hot encoding host_location

# first categorising host_location as Bristol, UK, Not_UK, unspecified
Air_BnB <- Air_BnB %>%
  mutate(
    host_location_cat = case_when(
      str_detect(host_location, regex("Bristol", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "Bristol",
      str_detect(host_location, regex("England|United Kingdom|UK", ignore_case = TRUE)) & 
        !str_detect(host_location, regex("Bristol", ignore_case = TRUE)) ~ "UK",
      !is.na(host_location) ~ "Not_UK",
      is.na(host_location) ~ "unspecified"
    )
  ) %>%
  mutate(host_location_cat = factor(host_location_cat))

# making one-hot encoded cols
one_hot <- model.matrix(~ 0 + host_location_cat, data = Air_BnB)

# simplifying column names (they are unusual without this)

# binding new cols to Air_BnB

Training Random Forest Model

Note: All training models have been commented out but their result summaries have been printed. This is to save computation in knitting the document.

set.seed(1234)

# nested resampling to utilise cross validation and bootstrapping. Intention is to give most robust model

# ensuring parallel processing is enabled
registerDoParallel(parallel::detectCores())

# setting train controls
train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "boot",          # bootstrapping
  number = 10,             # number of resamples
  allowParallel = TRUE
)

nested_train_control <- trainControl(
  method = "cv",          # using cross validation
  number = 5,             # number of folds
  allowParallel = TRUE
)

# running model
rf_model_mse <- train(
    formula,
  data = Air_BnB, # because of cross validation, using whole data set
  method = "rf",            # random forest
  metric = "RMSE",          # optimising for RMSE (root mean squared error)
  trControl = train_control, # Training control
  search_control = nested_train_control, # nested cross validation control
  allowParallel = TRUE
)

MSE_rf_model = rf_model_mse$finalModel # retrieving lowest RMSE model

# converting multipoligons to point geometries
POIs = pois %>%
  mutate(geometry = st_centroid(geometry))
# creating POI density score

# making sure Air_BnB_sf and POIs have the same CRS
Air_BnB_sf <- st_as_sf(Air_BnB, coords = c("longitude", "latitude"), crs = 4326)
Air_BnB_sf <- st_transform(Air_BnB_sf, crs = 3857)

POIs = st_transform(POIs, crs = 3857)

# adding latitude and longitude back in as variables
Air_BnB_sf = cbind(Air_BnB_sf, Air_BnB$latitude, Air_BnB$longitude)
# calculating basic POI density score for Air_BnB_sf

# setting 400m radius - this was determined by repeating with 300, 350, 400, 450, 500, and 600
radius = 400

# making buffers to determine how POIs are counted
Air_BnB_buffers <- st_buffer(Air_BnB_sf, dist = radius)

# Count POIs within each buffer
Air_BnB_sf$POIdensity_score <- sapply(st_geometry(Air_BnB_buffers), function(buffer) {
  sum(st_intersects(buffer, POIs, sparse = FALSE))
})

head(Air_BnB_sf$POIdensity_score)
## [1] 12 21 66  5 10 35

  theme_minimal() +

# # rerun model with AIR_BnB densities (represents supply of Air BnBs - important economic control)
radius1 = 400

Air_BnB_buffers <- st_buffer(Air_BnB_sf, dist = radius1)

# Count other AirBnB points within each buffer
Air_BnB_sf$AirBnBdensity_score <- sapply(1:nrow(Air_BnB_sf), function(i) {
  # Exclude the current AirBnB point from consideration
  other_points <- Air_BnB_sf[-i, ]

  # Get the buffer geometry
  buffer <- st_geometry(Air_BnB_buffers)[i]

  # Check if any other AirBnB points are within the buffer
  count <- sum(st_intersects(buffer, other_points, sparse = FALSE))

  # Return the count
  return(count)
})

Limitations and Future Work

Ultimately, the success of these model is limited by variable luxuary in the Air_BnBs. All the attribute data such as beds and location do not account for the luxuray of the appartments. As people we can look at pictures and immediately decide if a bathroom looks nice or not but that is not factored into any of the modelling. Location does not account for this at all. Even within the same block of flats, the appearance of bedrooms adn bathrooms can differ entirely. This could only be properly dealt with by utilising a convolutional neural network. This would still be limited by the validation data - the apparent luxury of an appartment is subjective. Either one person would have to grade 1000s of images themselves, firstly into bedroom, bathroom, exterioir, and shared_room and then into luxury rankings. Thsi would, of course, be entirely dependant on this one persons opinions. Alternatively, a crowd of people could all rank the apparent luxury of the apparetmnets shown in images and then an average could be taken but this would be even harder to implement. The only way i can see this working would be if Air BnB themselves added an apartment luxury ranking option for people to grade and then allow the people who have stayed their to verify whether they agree or not with said ranking in the reviews. - I cannot see this happening however since people can see the photos already and it is only the computer models which cannot understand the luxury of an apartment. If Air BnB were to implement this they could start effectively advising their users if they should increase or decrease their prices or if a location is good value.

Distance was useful but there was no measure of travel links. In this sense POI density became a measure of walkable access to amenities. Distance was euclidean but ideally this would have been replaced by distance via road networks. Fortunately, for Bristol there is no tube network which would surely complicate this.
